{
  "doc_id": "18094",
  "text": "Cortical regions, including the anterior cingulate, orbitofrontal and prefrontal cortices are decreased in volume in patients with MDD, [CITATION_1] and frontal-subcortical circuits are thought to play a key role in the regulation of motor, cognitive and motivational processes. [CITATION_2] Five anatomically and functionally discrete parallel loops connect specific areas of the prefrontal cortex and interconnect with functionally related brain areas. [CITATION_3] Among them, structural and functional abnormalities within neural systems, including frontal-subcortical circuits, are associated with the neurobiology of depression. [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] White matter abnormality can be seen as the substantial basis of the network dysfunction. In particular, it has been hypothesized that microstructural changes in the white matter of frontal-subcortical circuits lead to a \"disconnection syndrome\" between frontal and subcortical regions. [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] Converging evidence from postmortem and in vivo studies suggests that frontolimbic dysfunction plays an important role in the pathophysiology of MDD, [CITATION_9] [CITATION_10] [CITATION_11] whereas executive dysfunction, associated with compromised integrity of frontal structures and their subcortical connections, has also been reported in late-life depression. [CITATION_12] Recently, a thorough review of the neurocircuitry involved in depression combining functional and structural imaging with lesion evidence and histological material postulated that a system that links the medial prefrontal cortex and other related cortical areas to subcortical areas, such as the amygdala, the ventral striatum and pallidum, the medial thalamus and the hypothalamus, is centrally involved in mood disorders. [CITATION_13] The present metaanalysis gives strong evidence of a structural basis for the involvement of this neurocircuitry.",
